In a #small pot{}, combine @white rice{3/4%cup}, @water{1 1/4%cups}, and @salt{pinch}. Bring to
a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, wash and dry produce.

Halve @peach{1} and remove pit; thinly slice. Zest and quarter @lime{1}. Halve, core, and slice
@green bell pepper{1} into 1/4-inch strips. Trim @scallions{2}; cut whites into 1-inch pieces and
thinly slice greens. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%oz}. Roughly chop @peanuts{1/2%oz}.

In a #small bowl{}, toss peach slices with @sugar{1/2%tbsp} and a pinch of salt; set aside.

In a second small bowl, combine @soy sauce{2%tbsp}, @ginger paste{1%oz}, @Sweet Thai Chili Sauce{1%oz},
@peach jam{1}, juice from half the lime, and @pepper{}; set aside.

> For a milder sauce, use less ginger paste!

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @salmon{10%oz}; cook until
browned and cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes} per side.

> Fish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in pan used for chicken over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper,
scallion whites, salt, and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{5%minutes}.

Add peach slices (and any juices) to pan; cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @water{2%tbsp}; cook, stirring, until thickened and syrupy, ~{30-60%seconds} more.

Remove from heat; stir in @butter{1%tbsp} until melted.

Return pan with peach mixture to medium-low heat; add soy-ginger sauce. Cook, stirring, until sauce
has thickened and peach and bell pepper are tender, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in lime zest and half the cilantro.

Slice salmon crosswise.

Divide rice between shallow #bowls{}. Top with salmon, peach and bell pepper, and any remaining sauce
from pan. Garnish with peanuts, scallion greens, and remaining cilantro. Serve.